# Visual Identity System

Each “Where’s That Pokémon?” scene is illustrated using a distinct art style inspired by established visual eras and mediums from Pokémon history.

The goal is to make every page feel like stepping into a different part of the Pokémon universe while remaining visually authentic to the franchise.

Art styles are intentionally derived from recognizable Pokémon aesthetics across:
- video games
- trading cards
- anime
- manga
- promotional art
- diorama/clay styles
- retro pixel art
- watercolor illustrations
- cinematic CGI
- classic Sugimori-style rendering

This creates:
- visual variety
- nostalgia
- replayability
- collectibility
- and cross-generational appeal.

Examples:

Pallet Town
→ Game Boy Advance / DS pixel-art style

Cerulean City
→ Bright watercolor / classic anime film aesthetic

Saffron City
→ Neon cyberpunk-inspired pixel style based on urban game environments

Lavender Town
→ Dark manga / ghost-story watercolor hybrid

Safari Zone
→ Storybook field-guide illustration style

Rocket Warehouse
→ Industrial cinematic TCG full-art style

Cinnabar Island
→ Dramatic legendary-card splash-art style

Special Edition Pages:
- Claymation-inspired diorama scenes
- Black-and-white manga pages
- Vintage trading card print styles
- Hand-painted storybook spreads
- Pokémon Snap-inspired photography pages
- Low-poly Nintendo 64-inspired environments
- Modern 3D cel-shaded scenes

The project becomes not only a search-and-find experience, but also a celebration of Pokémon’s evolving artistic legacy.